"""
MKT Original Language Commentary — John chapter 8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-john-8-8.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json (chapter 8 tokens)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (semantic ranges, dispute levels)
- data/translation/notes/john.json (translation reasoning)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological baseline)

Key decisions in this range:
- vv.1–11 (pericope adulterae): absent from the oldest Greek MSS (P66, P75, Sinaiticus,
  Vaticanus) and early Fathers; internally marked as an insertion in many MSS that include
  it. Treated as a floating authentic tradition about Jesus, not composed by the Evangelist;
  commentary notes the textual situation per verse without dismissing the content.
- ἐγώ εἰμι (v.12, 24, 28, 58): consistent treatment: predicated forms (v.12 "I am the
  light") marked as self-disclosure; bare absolute forms (v.24, 28, 58) noted as invoking
  the divine name of Exod 3:14.
- κατὰ τὴν σάρκα (v.15): "according to the flesh" = operating within creaturely categories
  of perception and self-interest; not Paul's "sinful nature" but consistent with John's
  σάρξ = human realm (as established in 3:6 commentary).
- ὑψόω (v.28): "lift up" carries Johannine double meaning: crucifixion (the physical act)
  and glorification (exaltation) — established in 3:14 commentary, carried forward here.
- πρὶν Ἀβραὰμ γενέσθαι / ἐγώ εἰμι (v.58): the contrast between γίνομαι (to become,
  come into being — temporal, contingent) and εἰμί (to be — absolute, timeless) is the
  theological crux of the chapter and the reason for the stoning attempt.
- λαλιά vs λόγος (v.43): λαλιά = manner of speech, the form; λόγος = the word/message
  itself; the Evangelist distinguishes them deliberately.
- "the Evangelist" used throughout as authorial designation.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "8": {
    "1": '<p><em>Textual note:</em> The section John 7:53–8:11 (the <em>pericope adulterae</em>) is absent from the oldest and most reliable manuscripts: P66, P75, Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Vaticanus, and most early Syriac and Coptic witnesses. Where it does appear, many MSS mark it with an asterisk or obelos to signal doubt. Internal style and vocabulary also diverge from the Evangelist\'s usual register. The scholarly consensus is that the Evangelist did not write this passage; it is an ancient floating tradition about Jesus that entered the Gospel text at various points in transmission. Commentary on vv.1–11 treats the passage as historically credible tradition while noting that its original language and theology cannot be confidently assigned to the Fourth Evangelist.</p><p><strong>Ὄρος τῶν Ἐλαιῶν</strong> — the Mount of Olives. In Johannine chronology this is unusual; the Synoptics place Jesus there repeatedly during Passion Week (Luke 21:37–38), but the Evangelist does not otherwise describe a night retreat to Olivet. The detail matches the Lukan practice of Jesus teaching in the temple by day and lodging on the Mount at night — further evidence that this tradition preserved Synoptic-type material.</p>',

    "2": '<p><strong>ὄρθρου</strong> (<em>orthrou</em>) — "at dawn," the earliest part of the morning. The return to the temple at the first light of day establishes a pattern (consistent with Luke 21:38, where all the people came early to hear him). <strong>καθίσας ἐδίδασκεν</strong> — "he sat down and began teaching." The seated posture is the recognized posture of rabbinic teaching; the imperfect <em>edidasken</em> indicates continuous activity, not a single pronouncement. The crowd gathered (<em>pās ho laos proserchetō</em>, "all the people kept coming to him") — the scene before the interruption is one of sustained, welcomed teaching.</p>',

    "3": '<p><strong>οἱ γραμματεῖς καὶ οἱ Φαρισαῖοι</strong> — "the scribes and the Pharisees." This phrase is characteristic of the Synoptic Gospels, not of the Evangelist, who consistently uses "the Jews" for institutional opposition. Its appearance here is further stylistic evidence that the pericope derives from a different tradition. The word <strong>μοιχεία</strong> (<em>moicheia</em>, adultery) covers sexual intercourse by a married (or betrothed) woman with a man other than her husband; Mosaic law treated it as a capital offense involving both parties (Deut 22:22–24), but only the woman is brought here.</p>',

    "4": '<p><strong>ἐπ᾽ αὐτοφώρῳ</strong> (<em>ep\' autophōrō</em>) — "in the very act," literally "caught in the deed itself." The technical legal term implies witnesses were present. Under Mosaic law both parties to adultery were to be executed (Lev 20:10; Deut 22:22), yet no man is brought forward — a conspicuous gap that the questioners do not address. <strong>Διδάσκαλε</strong> (<em>Didaskale</em>) — "Teacher," the honorific address that frames the exchange as a legal consultation rather than an accusation.</p>',

    "5": '<p><strong>ἐν δὲ τῷ νόμῳ ἡμῖν Μωϋσῆς ἐνετείλατο</strong> — "Now Moses in the law commanded us." The citation is Deut 22:23–24 (betrothed woman) or Lev 20:10, which mandates death for adultery without specifying the mode; Deut 22:24 specifies stoning for the betrothed case. The questioners present this as a settled legal requirement: <strong>λιθοβολεῖσθαι</strong> (<em>lithoboleisthai</em>, to be stoned). The trap is legal: if Jesus endorses stoning, he appears to support action that Roman law forbade Jews to carry out (cf. 18:31 — Jews had no power of execution under Rome); if he opposes it, he contradicts Moses.</p>',

    "6": '<p><strong>τοῦτο δὲ ἔλεγον πειράζοντες αὐτόν</strong> — "this they were saying testing him." The present participle <em>peirázontes</em> identifies the motive explicitly: not justice for the woman but a legal snare to manufacture grounds for accusation (<strong>κατηγορεῖν</strong>). <strong>κατεκύπτω</strong> (<em>katekypsen</em>) — "stooped down" or "bent over." Then <strong>τῷ δακτύλῳ ἔγραφεν εἰς τὴν γῆν</strong> — "was writing on the ground with his finger." The imperfect <em>ēgraphen</em> (kept writing) indicates a sustained act rather than a single mark. The content of the writing is never stated; numerous traditions (the names of the accusers\' sins, OT scripture) are speculative. What the verb does is give Jesus a visible posture of non-engagement — he refuses the terms of their dilemma.</p>',

    "7": '<p><strong>ἐπέμενον ἐρωτῶντες</strong> — "they kept pressing, questioning." Two imperfects side by side: they persisted; Jesus had been writing. He cannot permanently ignore a direct question. <strong>ἀνέκυψεν</strong> (<em>anekypsen</em>, "he straightened up") is the same verb used in v.10. <strong>ὁ ἀναμάρτητος ὑμῶν</strong> — "the one among you who is without sin." <em>Anamártētos</em> (G361) is a hapax in the New Testament — it appears nowhere else. The adjective does not specify which sin; it does not say only the specific sin of adultery disqualifies. Its scope is general. <strong>πρῶτος ἐπ᾽ αὐτὴν βαλέτω λίθον</strong> — "let him be first to throw a stone at her." Jesus has not dismissed the law; he has placed its application back on the conscience of those who invoke it.</p>',

    "8": '<p><strong>πάλιν κατακύψας ἔγραφεν εἰς τὴν γῆν</strong> — "again, having stooped down, he was writing on the ground." The repetition of the posture (κατακύψας, "having bent over") and the resumed writing signal that Jesus is done speaking; the matter is now in their hands. The imperfect <em>ēgraphen</em> again: he was still writing as they processed what he had said. The act of writing may function as deliberate aversion of gaze — not watching them face the weight of their own consciences.</p>',

    "9": '<p><strong>εἷς καθ᾽ εἷς</strong> — "one by one," a distributive idiom. <strong>ἀρξάμενοι ἀπὸ τῶν πρεσβυτέρων</strong> — "beginning from the elders." The departure of the oldest first is natural: the most experienced have the most to be examined by, and perhaps the most visible social standing to lose. <strong>κατελείφθη μόνος</strong> — "was left alone." The perfect passive <em>kateleiphthē</em> gives finality to the abandonment: he was left, and the woman was in the middle (the spatial note is in the Greek — <em>οὖσα ἐν μέσῳ</em>). The accusers are gone; the accused remains.</p>',

    "10": '<p><strong>ἀνακύψας</strong> (<em>anakýpsas</em>) — "having straightened up." The Evangelist uses the same verb for Jesus\'s rising in v.7, giving the two moments a visual parallel. <strong>Γύναι</strong> (<em>Gynai</em>) — "Woman," the same address Jesus uses to his mother at Cana (2:4) and to Mary at the tomb (20:15); not dismissive but neutral and respectful in this register. <strong>ποῦ εἰσιν</strong> — "where are they?" The question invites the woman to register what has happened. <strong>οὐδείς σε κατέκρινεν</strong> — "has no one condemned you?" <em>Katakrinō</em> is the stronger verb — not <em>krinō</em> (to judge, evaluate) but to condemn with sentence.</p>',

    "11": '<p><strong>Οὐδείς, Κύριε</strong> — "No one, Lord/Sir." <em>Kyrie</em> here is ambiguous: it can be the respectful address "Sir" or the fuller Johannine confessional title "Lord." The woman\'s answer is bare and understated. <strong>οὐδὲ ἐγώ σε κατακρίνω</strong> — "neither do I condemn you." Jesus uses the same verb <em>katakrinō</em> the questioners had invoked by implication. The statement is not a declaration of innocence — it is a suspension of condemnation, releasing her from the immediate legal sentence. <strong>ἀπὸ τοῦ νῦν μηκέτι ἁμάρτανε</strong> — "from now on no longer sin." Present imperative of <em>hamartanō</em> with the negative <em>mēketi</em>: stop sinning — or, cease the ongoing practice. The instruction presupposes the reality of the sin without dwelling on it.</p>',

    "12": '<p><strong>ἐγώ εἰμι τὸ φῶς τοῦ κόσμου</strong> — "I am the light of the world." A predicated ego eimi — one of the seven great "I am + predicate" sayings in the Fourth Gospel. The immediate context is the Feast of Tabernacles (7:2); part of that celebration involved lighting four massive golden menorahs in the Court of Women (Mishnah Sukkah 5:2–3), whose light reportedly illuminated all Jerusalem. Jesus delivers this claim in or near that court (v.20) in the days following that festival — the imagery is not accidental. <strong>φῶς τῆς ζωῆς</strong> — "the light of life." The genitive is both attributive ("life-giving light") and appositive ("light, that is, life"). The Evangelist opened the Gospel with precisely this pairing: "In him was life, and the life was the light of men" (1:4).</p>',

    "13": '<p><strong>σύ περὶ σεαυτοῦ μαρτυρεῖς</strong> — "you are testifying about yourself." The Pharisees invoke legal principle: Mishnaic law (mKet. 2:9; mBB 5:7) disqualified self-testimony. The verb <em>martyreis</em> (present tense) marks their objection as a procedural challenge, not a substantive refutation of what he said. <strong>ἡ μαρτυρία σου οὐκ ἔστιν ἀληθής</strong> — "your testimony is not true (valid)." <em>Alēthēs</em> in this legal context means "valid, legally admissible" — not that his testimony is factually false, but that it fails the two-witness requirement.</p>',

    "14": '<p><strong>ἐγώ οἶδα πόθεν ἦλθον καὶ ποῦ ὑπάγω</strong> — "I know where I came from and where I am going." The verb is <em>oida</em> (perfect with present force: I have seen and so I know). The knowledge is rooted in his origin and destination — categories no human witness could verify or falsify. This is the fundamental asymmetry: the legal principle applies among equal parties; it cannot be applied to the one whose testimony uniquely concerns his own divine origin. <strong>ὑμεῖς δὲ οὐκ οἴδατε</strong> — "but you do not know." The same verb, the same perfect form — but opposite. Their ignorance of his origin is not lack of information; it is a failure of recognition that runs deeper than evidence.</p>',

    "15": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς κατὰ τὴν σάρκα κρίνετε</strong> — "you judge according to the flesh." <em>Kata tēn sarka</em> — "according to the flesh" — in the Johannine register established at 3:6: <em>sárx</em> is the human realm of natural perception, social categories, and surface appearance. Judgment <em>kata sarka</em> is judgment operating entirely within creaturely categories: what can be seen, verified by social standing, and evaluated by the two-witness rule. <strong>ἐγὼ οὐ κρίνω οὐδένα</strong> — "I judge no one." This is not a permanent renunciation of judgment (cf. v.16; 5:22, 27–30), but a claim about his current mission: the Son came not to condemn the world but to save it (3:17).</p>',

    "16": '<p><strong>ἀληθινή</strong> (<em>alēthinē</em>) — "true, genuine, real." The Evangelist distinguishes <em>alēthēs</em> (factually true, honest) from <em>alēthinos</em> (genuine, belonging to ultimate reality — the real thing as opposed to the copy or shadow). Jesus\'s judgment is <em>alēthinos</em>: not just accurate but of a different ontological order. <strong>ὅτι μόνος οὐκ εἰμί</strong> — "because I am not alone." The basis of the judgment\'s validity is not a second human witness but the presence of the Father. The two-witness principle is fulfilled by Father and Son — not by two human observers.</p>',

    "17": '<p><strong>ἐν τῷ νόμῳ δὲ τῷ ὑμετέρῳ</strong> — "in your law." The possessive <em>hymeterō</em> ("your") is notable: Jesus speaks of the Torah as theirs, not as foreign. The reference is to Deut 17:6 and 19:15 — the rule requiring two or three witnesses to establish a matter. <strong>δύο ἀνθρώπων ἡ μαρτυρία ἀληθής ἐστιν</strong> — "the testimony of two humans is true (valid)." Jesus is applying their own procedural rule against their objection: by the Torah standard, two witnesses suffice. He and the Father constitute two witnesses — and by that standard the legal challenge fails.</p>',

    "18": '<p><strong>ἐγώ εἰμι ὁ μαρτυρῶν περὶ ἐμαυτοῦ</strong> — "I am the one who testifies about myself." The predicated ego eimi here is functional: one witness. <strong>καὶ μαρτυρεῖ περὶ ἐμοῦ ὁ πέμψας με πατήρ</strong> — "and the Father who sent me testifies about me." Two witnesses, as the law requires. The Father\'s testimony is given through the works Jesus does (5:36) and through the divine voice at his baptism and transfiguration (Synoptic parallels); in the Evangelist\'s framework, the works Jesus performs are the Father\'s own witness.</p>',

    "19": '<p><strong>ποῦ ἐστιν ὁ πατήρ σου</strong> — "where is your father?" Their question is sarcastic — they cannot see the Father, so they reject the claim of a second witness. The question also carries an implicit slur: where is this father you keep invoking, implying illegitimacy or delusion. <strong>εἰ ἐμὲ ᾔδειτε, καὶ τὸν πατέρα μου ᾔδειτε ἄν</strong> — "if you knew me, you would know my Father also." The pluperfect <em>ēideite</em> in both clauses: the knowledge of Jesus and the knowledge of the Father are inseparable — one cannot know the Father by another path than through the Son (cf. 14:7).</p>',

    "20": '<p><strong>ἐν τῷ γαζοφυλακίῳ</strong> — "near the treasury," or more precisely "the treasury-room area." The <em>gazophylakion</em> was located in the Court of Women, where thirteen trumpet-shaped collection receptacles stood and where the great lamps of Tabernacles had been lit. Jesus teaches in this very space, surrounded by the symbols his claim is now overturning. <strong>οὔπω ἐληλύθει ἡ ὥρα αὐτοῦ</strong> — "his hour had not yet come." The Evangelist\'s repeated phrase (cf. 7:30) marks divine timing: what the crowd or the authorities attempt cannot succeed until Jesus himself moves toward it. The "hour" in Johannine theology is the crucifixion-glorification (cf. 12:23, 27; 13:1; 17:1).</p>',

    "21": '<p><strong>ὑπάγω</strong> (<em>hypagō</em>) — "I am going away." The Evangelist uses this verb repeatedly for Jesus\'s departure through death (7:33; 13:3; 14:2; 16:5, 7). The audience hears it as physical departure; the Evangelist intends the whole arc of death, resurrection, and return to the Father. <strong>ζητήσετέ με καὶ ἐν τῇ ἁμαρτίᾳ ὑμῶν ἀποθανεῖσθε</strong> — "you will look for me and you will die in your sin." The singular <em>hamartia</em> here (v.21) shifts to plural in v.24 — the singular frames their fundamental failure of orientation, the plural encompasses all its expressions. The seeking is too late: the one who could give life will be gone.</p>',

    "22": '<p><strong>μήτι ἀποκτενεῖ ἑαυτόν</strong> — "Will he kill himself?" The speculation is darkly ironic. The Evangelist has already told readers that Jesus will indeed be "lifted up" through death — but his death will be an act of self-giving, not suicide. Under Jewish law, self-murder was a grave violation; the thought is contemptuous. But the Evangelist allows the irony to stand: in a sense they are correct that no one can take his life from him — he lays it down of himself (10:18). Their mockery accidentally touches the truth.</p>',

    "23": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς ἐκ τῶν κάτω ἐστέ, ἐγὼ ἐκ τῶν ἄνω εἰμί</strong> — "you are from below; I am from above." The spatial contrast is the Evangelist\'s characteristic vertical ontology: κάτω (below) = the world as it presently is, cut off from God; ἄνω (above) = the sphere of God\'s presence. The same contrast governs the Nicodemus dialogue (3:3, 31). <strong>ὑμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου τούτου ἐστέ, ἐγὼ οὐκ εἰμὶ ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου τούτου</strong> — the synonymous parallel: "of this world" and "from below" are interchangeable. Jesus is not a product of this world\'s generative process; his origin is categorically other.</p>',

    "24": '<p><strong>ἐὰν γὰρ μὴ πιστεύσητε ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι</strong> — "for unless you believe that I am." The phrase <em>egō eimi</em> here has no predicate; "he" is supplied by most translations but is absent from the Greek. This is the absolute ego eimi — the divine name of Exod 3:14 (LXX: <em>egō eimi ho ōn</em>, "I am the one who is"). The same construction appears at 8:28 and — most explicitly — at 8:58. To miss its resonance here is to miss the claim: Jesus is identifying himself with the God who spoke to Moses. The consequence of unbelief is death in sins (plural now — all the acts of sin that flow from the core failure of not knowing him).</p>',

    "25": '<p><strong>σὺ τίς εἶ</strong> — "Who are you?" After the ego eimi of v.24, the question is deliberately obtuse or genuinely bewildered. <strong>τὴν ἀρχὴν ὅ τι καὶ λαλῶ ὑμῖν</strong> — the reply is among the most debated in John. The Greek is compressed: <em>tēn archēn</em> can be accusative of time ("from the beginning") or an adverb meaning "at all" or "primarily." The most defensible reading: "Exactly what I have been telling you from the beginning." Jesus points back to the whole discourse — his claims have not changed; the revelation has been consistent. Demanding a new or different answer misunderstands how he speaks.</p>',

    "26": '<p><strong>πολλὰ ἔχω περὶ ὑμῶν λαλεῖν καὶ κρίνειν</strong> — "I have many things to say about you and to judge." The potential for judgment is enormous — Jesus holds much that is true about them that could be spoken as condemnation. But his restraint is deliberate: <strong>ὁ πέμψας με ἀληθής ἐστιν</strong> — "the one who sent me is trustworthy/true." <em>Alēthēs</em> here: the Father is reliable, and it is only what he has heard from the Father that Jesus speaks to the world. He limits himself to the Father\'s commission, not to the full extent of what could be said.</p>',

    "27": '<p><strong>οὐκ ἔγνωσαν ὅτι τὸν πατέρα αὐτοῖς ἔλεγεν</strong> — "they did not know that he was speaking to them of the Father." The Evangelist steps back to note the failure of comprehension explicitly. The verb <em>egnōsan</em> (aorist of <em>ginōskō</em>) marks the moment: there was a point of potential recognition that did not happen. The gap between what Jesus says and what they hear is not a communication failure on his part; the Evangelist has been documenting this failure of perception throughout the chapter.</p>',

    "28": '<p><strong>ὅταν ὑψώσητε τὸν υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου</strong> — "when you lift up the Son of Man." <em>Hypsoō</em> (G5312) carries Johannine double meaning: the physical lifting on the cross (crucifixion) and the exaltation-glorification — the Evangelist has established this in 3:14 ("the Son of Man must be lifted up as Moses lifted up the serpent"). The audience hears only execution; the Evangelist means both. <strong>τότε γνώσεσθε ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι</strong> — "then you will know that I am." The bare ego eimi again (cf. v.24), and the knowing it produces is triggered by the cross event itself. Crucifixion becomes revelation — a signature Johannine paradox.</p>',

    "29": '<p><strong>ὁ πέμψας με μετ᾽ ἐμοῦ ἐστιν· οὐκ ἀφῆκέν με μόνον</strong> — "the one who sent me is with me; he has not left me alone." The aorist <em>aphēken</em> ("has left") is negated: there has been no moment of abandonment. This stands in deliberate contrast with the cry of dereliction in the Synoptics (Matt 27:46 // Mark 15:34 — "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?"); the Evangelist\'s Passion does not include that cry. Here the claim is total: <strong>τὰ ἀρεστὰ αὐτῷ ποιῶ πάντοτε</strong> — "I always do the things that please him." <em>Pantote</em> (always) is absolute: the obedience is without exception.</p>',

    "30": '<p><strong>ταῦτα αὐτοῦ λαλοῦντος πολλοὶ ἐπίστευσαν εἰς αὐτόν</strong> — "as he was speaking these things, many believed in him." The present participle <em>lalountos</em> places the believing in the midst of the discourse — it was happening while the words were still being spoken. The Evangelist marks this transition because vv.31–59 will show that "believing" exists on a spectrum: many who "believed" in v.30 will by v.59 be attempting to stone him. The Evangelist is about to interrogate the quality and durability of faith.</p>',

    "31": '<p><strong>τοὺς πεπιστευκότας αὐτῷ Ἰουδαίους</strong> — "the Jews who had believed him." The perfect participle <em>pepisteukotas</em> (those who have believed) distinguishes this group from the hostile interlocutors. <strong>ἐὰν ὑμεῖς μείνητε ἐν τῷ λόγῳ τῷ ἐμῷ</strong> — "if you abide in my word." <em>Menō</em> (to remain, abide, stay) is among the most theologically freighted verbs in the Johannine writings — it will dominate John 15 (the vine and branches). Here it is the condition of genuine discipleship: not a momentary assent but sustained dwelling in his word. The conditional framing (ἐάν + subjunctive) makes the outcome dependent on the continuing choice to abide.</p>',

    "32": '<p><strong>γνώσεσθε τὴν ἀλήθειαν</strong> — "you will know the truth." The future <em>gnōsesthe</em> is experiential knowing (<em>ginōskō</em>), not merely intellectual assent. <em>Alētheia</em> in Johannine usage is not abstract epistemological truth but the reality that Jesus himself embodies and reveals — "I am the way, the truth, and the life" (14:6). To know the truth is to know him. <strong>ἡ ἀλήθεια ἐλευθερώσει ὑμᾶς</strong> — "the truth will set you free." <em>Eleutherōsei</em> (future of <em>eleutheroō</em>, G1659) — to liberate from moral, ceremonial, or mortal liability. The liberty is not philosophical but ontological: release from the condition described in v.34.</p>',

    "33": '<p><strong>σπέρμα Ἀβραάμ ἐσμεν</strong> — "we are Abraham\'s seed/descendants." <em>Sperma</em> is the biological/genealogical term — physical descent. This is factually true (Jesus acknowledges it in v.37), but the Evangelist is already marking the distinction between physical descent and covenantal inheritance. <strong>οὐδενὶ δεδουλεύκαμεν πώποτε</strong> — "we have never been enslaved to anyone, ever." The perfect <em>dedouleukamen</em> is a remarkable historical claim: Israel had been enslaved in Egypt, Babylon, and was at that moment under Roman occupation. The claim operates at the level of covenantal identity rather than political history — they understand themselves as a free people by covenant even when politically subject.</p>',

    "34": '<p><strong>πᾶς ὁ ποιῶν τὴν ἁμαρτίαν δοῦλός ἐστιν τῆς ἁμαρτίας</strong> — "everyone who practices sin is a slave of sin." The present participle <em>poiōn</em> marks habitual, ongoing practice — not a single act but the pattern of life. <em>Doulos</em> (G1401) is the Greek term for slave — not servant (that would be <em>diakonos</em> or <em>hyperetēs</em>), but one who is owned, whose will is subject to another\'s. <em>Tēs hamartias</em> is the genitive of ownership: sin is the master. The argument draws on Stoic philosophical commonplace (only the wise are truly free) but reframes it: the bondage is moral and spiritual, not social, and the slave is everyone who sins — including those who claim covenant freedom.</p>',

    "35": '<p><strong>ὁ δὲ δοῦλος οὐ μένει ἐν τῇ οἰκίᾳ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα</strong> — "the slave does not remain in the household forever." The slave\'s position is contingent — he can be sold, freed, or expelled. <strong>ὁ υἱὸς μένει εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα</strong> — "the son remains forever." <em>Menō</em> again — abiding is the characteristic of the son, not the slave. The argument employs the structure of household law: a slave\'s tenure is dependent on the master\'s will; a son\'s membership is by birth and permanent. Jesus is the Son in whom abiding is secured.</p>',

    "36": '<p><strong>ἐὰν οὖν ὁ υἱὸς ὑμᾶς ἐλευθερώσῃ</strong> — "if therefore the Son sets you free." The conditional is not doubtful — it is the offer. <strong>ὄντως ἐλεύθεροι ἔσεσθε</strong> — "you will be truly free." <em>Ontōs</em> (truly, genuinely, really) is the adverb of genuine reality as opposed to appearance or claim. The freedom that Abraham\'s physical lineage cannot give (v.33), and that the law cannot give because the law requires obedience that enslaved people cannot render, the Son can give — because he is the permanent member of the household who can confer the status of adoption.</p>',

    "37": '<p><strong>οἶδα ὅτι σπέρμα Ἀβραάμ ἐστε</strong> — "I know that you are Abraham\'s seed." Jesus does not contest the genealogy. The pivot is: <strong>ὁ λόγος ὁ ἐμὸς οὐ χωρεῖ ἐν ὑμῖν</strong> — "my word finds no place (makes no progress) in you." <em>Chōreō</em> (G5562) means to make room, to advance, to have space to move — it is used of water spreading or of a crowd making room. His word has no room to penetrate, no space to move within them. Physical descent from Abraham is not at issue; the failure is receptivity to the word.</p>',

    "38": '<p><strong>ἃ ἐγὼ ἑώρακα παρὰ τῷ πατρί, λαλῶ</strong> — "what I have seen with the Father, I speak." The perfect <em>heōraka</em> (I have seen, and the seeing is complete and its result stands): Jesus\'s speech is entirely derived from prior vision of the Father. He is not speculating or inventing. <strong>καὶ ὑμεῖς οὖν ἃ ἠκούσατε παρὰ τοῦ πατρός, ποιεῖτε</strong> — "and you, therefore, do what you have heard from your father." The parallel construction — I have seen my Father / you have heard your father — sets up the disclosure of vv.44: the two "fathers" are not the same.</p>',

    "39": '<p><strong>ὁ πατὴρ ἡμῶν Ἀβραάμ ἐστιν</strong> — "Abraham is our father." Their claim is genealogical — unchanged from v.33. Jesus\'s reply shifts the ground entirely: <strong>εἰ τέκνα τοῦ Ἀβραάμ ἐστε, τὰ ἔργα τοῦ Ἀβραὰμ ἐποιεῖτε</strong> — "if you were Abraham\'s children, you would do Abraham\'s works." The key distinction: <em>sperma</em> (seed, v.37) — biological connection; <em>tekna</em> (children) — relational and behavioral connection. Physical descent and spiritual kinship can diverge. The imperfect <em>epoieite</em> in the apodosis (contrary-to-fact conditional): they would have been doing Abraham\'s deeds — but they are not.</p>',

    "40": '<p><strong>ἄνθρωπον ὃς τὴν ἀλήθειαν ὑμῖν λελάληκα</strong> — "a man who has spoken to you the truth." The perfect <em>lelalēka</em> marks the full extent of his disclosure to them — all the truth he has spoken stands on record. Abraham received heavenly visitors and showed hospitality; Abraham believed God and it was counted as righteousness (Gen 15:6). <strong>τοῦτο Ἀβραὰμ οὐκ ἐποίησεν</strong> — "Abraham did not do this" — seek to kill a messenger of God who has told him the truth from God. The contrast condemns: their conduct resembles not Abraham\'s but someone else\'s.</p>',

    "41": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς ποιεῖτε τὰ ἔργα τοῦ πατρὸς ὑμῶν</strong> — "you are doing the works of your father." The identity of this father has not yet been named, but the accusation is pointed. Their counter-claim: <strong>ἡμεῖς ἐκ πορνείας οὐ γεγεννήμεθα</strong> — "we were not born of sexual immorality." The word <em>porneia</em> (G4202) here is possibly a barb aimed at Jesus\'s own birth (a counteraccusation of illegitimacy), or it echoes the OT prophetic use of <em>porneia</em> for Israel\'s idolatrous unfaithfulness to God (Hos 1–2; Ezek 16). Either way they are claiming legitimate, exclusive descent: <strong>ἕνα πατέρα ἔχομεν τὸν θεόν</strong> — "we have one Father, God." The Shema (Deut 6:4) is behind the claim.</p>',

    "42": '<p><strong>εἰ ὁ θεὸς πατὴρ ὑμῶν ἦν, ἠγαπᾶτε ἂν ἐμέ</strong> — "if God were your Father, you would love me." Second class conditional (εἰ + indicative imperfect; ἂν + indicative imperfect): contrary to fact. <em>Agapaō</em> (G25, dispute level 3) — the love that is covenantal orientation and commitment, not merely affection. The argument: God\'s children recognize and love the Son of God; failure to love him is evidence that God is not in fact their father in the sense they claim. <strong>ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐξῆλθον</strong> — "I came forth from God." The verb <em>exerchomai</em> (came out, emerged from) describes origin: not just mission (sent) but derivation (came out of).</p>',

    "43": '<p><strong>τὴν λαλιὰν τὴν ἐμήν</strong> / <strong>τὸν λόγον τὸν ἐμόν</strong> — the verse pairs two near-synonyms to distinguish them. <em>Lalia</em> (G2981) — manner of speech, mode of discourse, how he speaks. <em>Logos</em> (G3056, dispute level 3) — the word itself, the content and message. They cannot understand his manner of speaking because they are unable to hear his message. The incapacity to hear the deeper content (<em>logos</em>) produces incomprehension of the surface form (<em>lalia</em>). The failure of hearing is not perceptual but volitional and relational.</p>',

    "44": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ πατρὸς τοῦ διαβόλου ἐστέ</strong> — "you are of your father the devil." The Greek is slightly ambiguous — <em>tou patros tou diabolou</em> can be "of the father, the devil" (the devil is your father) or "of the father of the devil" (a phrase some MSS resolve by punctuation). The dominant reading, supported by context: the devil is their father. <strong>ἀνθρωποκτόνος ἦν ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς</strong> — "he was a murderer from the beginning." <em>Anthrōpoktonos</em> (G443, murder of humans) — a compound found nowhere else in the NT. "From the beginning" may refer to the fall of humanity through the serpent\'s deception (Gen 3) or to Cain\'s murder. <strong>οὐκ ἔστηκεν ἐν τῇ ἀληθείᾳ</strong> — "he does not stand in the truth." The perfect <em>estēken</em>: there is no point at which the devil took a stand in truth. <strong>ὅτι ψεύστης ἐστὶν καὶ ὁ πατὴρ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "because he is a liar and the father of it (lies)." <em>Pseudos</em> (the lie) is what the devil generates; it is his native produce.</p>',

    "45": '<p><strong>ὅτι δὲ ἐγὼ τὴν ἀλήθειαν λέγω, οὐ πιστεύετέ μοι</strong> — "but because I speak the truth, you do not believe me." The conjunction <em>de</em> + causal <em>hoti</em> marks the paradox: it is precisely because he tells the truth that they disbelieve. If he were lying — as the father of lies produces — they would be more at home with it. Their unbelief is not a neutral failure but a diagnostic indicator of spiritual paternity. The present tense <em>pisteúete</em> marks the ongoing state of non-belief.</p>',

    "46": '<p><strong>τίς ἐξ ὑμῶν ἐλέγχει με περὶ ἁμαρτίας</strong> — "which of you convicts me of sin?" <em>Elegchō</em> (G1651) is the legal term: to convict, to prove guilty by evidence. The challenge is real: bring evidence of sin. The silence that follows is itself the answer. <strong>εἰ ἀλήθειαν λέγω, διὰ τί ὑμεῖς οὐ πιστεύετέ μοι</strong> — "if I tell the truth, why do you not believe me?" The rhetorical structure is a legal argument: you cannot prove me guilty; I am telling the truth; therefore your unbelief is inexplicable on grounds of evidence — it must have a different cause, which v.47 will identify.</p>',

    "47": '<p><strong>ὁ ὢν ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ τὰ ῥήματα τοῦ θεοῦ ἀκούει</strong> — "the one who is of God hears the words of God." The present participle <em>ho ōn</em> ("the one who is") — being of God is a present, ongoing condition. <em>Rhēmata</em> (individual utterances, words spoken) rather than <em>logos</em> (the comprehensive word) — yet the force is equivalent: those who belong to God are attuned to his speech. <strong>διὰ τοῦτο ὑμεῖς οὐκ ἀκούετε, ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ οὐκ ἐστέ</strong> — "for this reason you do not hear, because you are not of God." The diagnosis closes the argument of the chapter: the failure to hear is not intellectual but ontological — a question of origin and belonging.</p>',

    "48": '<p><strong>Σαμαρίτης εἶ σύ</strong> — "you are a Samaritan." The accusation carries multiple insults: ethnic (mixed-blood, non-pure Israelite), religious (Samaritans rejected the Jerusalem temple and most of the prophetic writings), and social (Samaritans were despised by Judeans). <strong>καὶ δαιμόνιον ἔχεις</strong> — "and you have a demon." The word is <em>daimonion</em> (G1140, a lesser demonic being) rather than the stronger <em>diabolos</em> (devil). To attribute inspired speech to demonic influence is their only available counter to claims they cannot refute — it was the same accusation made in response to his exorcisms (Mark 3:22 // Matt 12:24).</p>',

    "49": '<p><strong>ἐγὼ δαιμόνιον οὐκ ἔχω</strong> — "I do not have a demon." The flat denial. <strong>ἀλλὰ τιμῶ τὸν πατέρα μου</strong> — "but I honor my Father." <em>Timaō</em> (G5091) — to honor, to ascribe value to. Jesus frames his entire ministry as honor of the Father; to call him demon-possessed is to dishonor the Father whose work he does. <strong>καὶ ὑμεῖς ἀτιμάζετέ με</strong> — "and you dishonor me." The contrast: he honors; they dishonor. The verbal root <em>timē</em> (honor) is the standard language of shame-and-honor culture — they have publicly shamed him, which in their framework is the appropriate response to a false teacher.</p>',

    "50": '<p><strong>ἐγὼ δὲ οὐ ζητῶ τὴν δόξαν μου</strong> — "but I do not seek my own glory." <em>Zēteō</em> (G2212, to seek, to pursue) — Jesus is not in a competition for honor. <em>Doxa</em> (G1391) — glory, honor, reputation. The point is not humility as virtue but a statement about his mission structure: his glory comes from the Father (v.54), not from human approval. <strong>ἔστιν ὁ ζητῶν καὶ κρίνων</strong> — "there is one who seeks and judges." The Father seeks the Son\'s glory and judges those who withhold it. The passive vindication of Jesus is left to God, not pursued by Jesus himself.</p>',

    "51": '<p><strong>ἐάν τις τὸν ἐμὸν λόγον τηρήσῃ, θάνατον οὐ μὴ θεωρήσῃ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα</strong> — "if anyone keeps my word, he will certainly never see death forever." <em>Tēreō</em> (G5083) is "to keep, guard, observe" — the same verb used for keeping commandments; it implies sustained, careful obedience. <em>Thanatos</em> (G2288) — death. <strong>θεωρήσῃ</strong> (aorist subjunctive of <em>theōreō</em>) — to behold, to witness as a spectator. The strong double negative <em>ou mē</em> + subjunctive is the most emphatic negation Greek allows: absolutely will not. <em>Eis ton aiōna</em> — "into the age, forever." The claim is not that the believer will not die physically, but that the experience of death as ultimate terminus — as the last word — will not happen to them (cf. 11:26).</p>',

    "52": '<p><strong>νῦν ἐγνώκαμεν ὅτι δαιμόνιον ἔχεις</strong> — "now we know that you have a demon." Their diagnosis has been confirmed to their satisfaction: his claim about death defies observable fact. <strong>Ἀβραὰμ ἀπέθανεν καὶ οἱ προφῆται</strong> — "Abraham died and the prophets [died]." The aorist <em>apethanen</em> is simple past: Abraham died. The prophets died. These are facts. If keeping Jesus\'s word prevents death, and Abraham died, then either Abraham did not keep the word, or Jesus is deluded. They choose the latter. <strong>γεύσηται θανάτου</strong> — "taste of death." The idiom "taste death" (cf. Heb 2:9) is a metaphor for the experience of dying; in v.51 Jesus used "see death." Both idioms mean the same: encounter death as ultimate reality.</p>',

    "53": '<p><strong>μὴ σὺ μείζων εἶ τοῦ πατρὸς ἡμῶν Ἀβραάμ</strong> — "you are not greater than our father Abraham, are you?" The Greek particle <em>mē</em> expects a negative answer: surely not? Their question is sarcastic; they expect him to back down. The Evangelist is setting up the answer: yes, actually, he is greater — not merely because he makes large claims, but because he pre-exists Abraham (v.58). <strong>τίνα σεαυτὸν ποιεῖς</strong> — "who do you make yourself?" The verb <em>poieō</em> (to make, to do) implies fabrication — they accuse him of self-construction, of inventing a greatness that is not real. The same charge of self-promotion will be made at the cross (19:7, 12).</p>',

    "54": '<p><strong>ἐὰν ἐγὼ δοξάζω ἐμαυτόν, ἡ δόξα μου οὐδέν ἐστιν</strong> — "if I glorify myself, my glory is nothing." The conditional (ἐάν + subjunctive) is logically possible but not actual: he does not self-glorify. Self-generated glory is empty — it has no external referent. <strong>ὃν ὑμεῖς λέγετε ὅτι θεὸς ἡμῶν ἐστιν</strong> — "whom you say is your God." Jesus deliberately turns their own language back on them: this is the God they claim. <strong>ἐστιν ὁ δοξάζων με</strong> — "it is he who glorifies me." The Father\'s glorification of the Son is not future only — it is ongoing in the works Jesus does and will reach its climax in the cross-resurrection event (12:28; 17:5).</p>',

    "55": '<p><strong>καὶ οὐκ ἐγνώκατε αὐτόν, ἐγὼ δὲ οἶδα αὐτόν</strong> — "and you have not known him, but I know him." The contrast of verbs is significant: <em>egnōkate</em> (perfect of <em>ginōskō</em>) — the relational, experiential knowing that grows over time — is what they lack. <em>Oida</em> (the knowing that comes from having seen) — is what Jesus has. His knowing of the Father is not derived from revelation given to him; it is immediate, direct seeing of the one from whom he came (cf. v.38). <strong>κἂν εἴπω ὅτι οὐκ οἶδα αὐτόν, ἔσομαι ὅμοιος ὑμῖν ψεύστης</strong> — "and if I said I did not know him, I would be a liar like you." He cannot deny what he knows without becoming what the devil is (v.44).</p>',

    "56": '<p><strong>Ἀβραὰμ ὁ πατὴρ ὑμῶν ἠγαλλιάσατο ἵνα ἴδῃ τὴν ἡμέραν τὴν ἐμήν</strong> — "Abraham your father rejoiced that he would see my day." The aorist <em>ēgalliasato</em> marks a completed act of joy. <em>Agalliaō</em> (G21) is exultant, leaping gladness — stronger than ordinary happiness. The content: <em>tēn hēmeran tēn emēn</em> — "my day." Jewish tradition associated Abraham\'s joy with the birth of Isaac (Gen 21:6), with the vision of the future (Gen 15:17 — the smoking firepot passing between the covenant pieces), or with the Aqedah where Abraham "saw" God\'s provision. The Evangelist does not specify which moment; what matters is that Abraham looked forward to a day that was Jesus\'s own — and saw it, and was glad.</p>',

    "57": '<p><strong>πεντήκοντα ἔτη οὔπω ἔχεις</strong> — "you are not yet fifty years old." The age of fifty was not chosen arbitrarily: it was the upper limit of Levitical service in the tabernacle (Num 4:3; 8:25). In rabbinic thought, fifty represented full maturity — the age at which wisdom was complete. The point is the absurdity of the claim: how could someone not yet a mature adult have had contact with a patriarch dead for two thousand years? Their objection assumes temporal proximity as the only mode of encounter — which is exactly the assumption Jesus dismantles in v.58.</p>',

    "58": '<p><strong>πρὶν Ἀβραὰμ γενέσθαι, ἐγώ εἰμι</strong> — "before Abraham was born (came into being), I am." The theological climax of the chapter, and arguably of all of John 8. Two verbs in deliberate contrast: <strong>γενέσθαι</strong> (aorist infinitive of <em>ginomai</em>) — to come into being, to begin to exist, the verb of temporal origination used throughout the Prologue for what "became" in creation (1:3, 6, 10); and <strong>εἰμί</strong> (present indicative of <em>eimi</em>) — to be, in the absolute, timeless sense. Abraham "became"; Jesus simply "is." The grammar refuses to put Jesus inside the same temporal category as Abraham. The bare <em>egō eimi</em> — absolute, without predicate — is the divine name of Exod 3:14 (LXX: <em>egō eimi ho ōn</em>). The Jewish audience understands immediately: this is why they reach for stones.</p>',

    "59": '<p><strong>ἦραν οὖν λίθους ἵνα βάλωσιν ἐπ᾽ αὐτόν</strong> — "therefore they lifted up stones in order to throw them at him." The inferential <em>oun</em> ("therefore"): the stoning attempt is the direct consequence of the ego eimi of v.58. Under Mosaic law, blasphemy — claiming to be God — was a capital offense requiring stoning (Lev 24:16). Their response is not irrational violence; it is the application of Torah to what they heard as the worst possible blasphemy. The Evangelist presents their action as legally coherent and spiritually catastrophic simultaneously. <strong>Ἰησοῦς δὲ ἐκρύβη καὶ ἐξῆλθεν ἐκ τοῦ ἱεροῦ</strong> — "but Jesus hid himself and went out of the temple." The verb <em>ekrybē</em> (aorist passive of <em>kryptō</em>, to hide) is the only place in the Fourth Gospel where Jesus conceals himself from arrest in this way. His hour has not yet come (v.20); he withdraws until it does.</p>',
  }
}


